<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Juniperus grandis </i>is a long-lived conifer that may reach 3000 years of age and 15 m in height. Cones mature in 2 years. Birds and mammals disperse the fleshy cones and seeds. Warm stratification followed by cold stratification enhances germination. Seed establishment occurs under shrubs and on mineral soil. The species is relatively shade intolerant (Dealy 1990, Tirmenstein 1999g). <br/>
<br/>
Traditionally, <i>J. occidentalis </i>involved two forms: var<i>. occidentalis </i>(western juniper) and var. <i>australis </i>(mountain juniper; Hickman 1993). Using sequence and random amplified polymorphic DNA (RAPD) data, Adams et al. (2006) have shown the varieties to be distant; they are now called <i>J. grandis </i>and <i>J. occidentalis</i>. In addition, they differ in their essential oils (Adams 2004) and in dioecy: <i>J. occidentalis </i>is monoecious while <i>J. grandis </i>is dioecious. Both species hybridize with <i>J. osteosperma </i>in the Warner and White mountains (Dealy 1990, Tirmenstein 1999g). We follow Adams and use the name <i>J. grandis</i>. <br/>
<br/>
Both species are constituents of extensive Great Basin woodlands, but stands of <i>J. grandis </i>also occur as small enclaves, typically on glaciated outcrops, in the montane and subalpine Sierra Nevada. At this time, the national classification (NatureServe 2007a) includes the two species in the <i>Juniperus occidentalis </i>alliance. Work in California has focused on <i>J. grandis </i>in the Sierra Nevada. We need more effort to understand the vegetation relationships of both species in transmontane California. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
