    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Db, Dd-f, Dj-l). Stands in the Bodie Hills, and throughout the section mix with those of the <i>Cercocarpus ledifolius, Pinus jeffreyi,</i> and <i>Pinus monophylla</i> alliances (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b, Thorne et al. 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba). A single stand of <i>J. grandis</i> found on Soldier Ridge in the Yolla Bolly Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Keeler-Wolf 1974) occupies fine-grained, sterile soils with stands of the <i>Quercus garryana</i> var. <i>fruticosa</i> alliance. This disjunction from the Sierra Nevada stands is noteworthy (Sawyer 2006).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Eh, Ej-k, Em-r, Et-u). High-elevation stands in Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b) and generally in the section (Potter 1998) occupy shallow soils of either volcanic flows or granitic rock (Fites- Kaufman et al. 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb, Ff). Individual trees and small stands are known in the Inyo and Panamint mountains (Griffin and Critchfield 1972).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Be, Bh). Stands occur in the San Bernardino and San Gabriel mountains (Minnich 2007, Minnich and Everett 2001, Wangler and Minnich 1996).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The ecology of <i>Juniperus grandis </i>stands in transmontane California is similar to that of <i>J. occidentalis, </i>but those at montane and subalpine elevations differ. We expect the conditions to be similar to open stands of the <i>Pinus contorta </i>ssp. <i>murrayana </i>alliance. Fire return intervals vary. On the west side of the Sierra Nevada, stand-replacing events are several hundred years apart (van Wagtendonk and Fites-Kaufman et al. 2007). </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
